Comment:
Yeah, I've really enjoyed his portayal. Some stuff in the films aside (I mean five films it won't be perfect), he is the closet in the look and idea of what Ian Fleming wrote. Previously Pierce was the "compromise" versus prior just making him a lot more idk...sauve and more wisecracking. I do miss a more eccentric fun Q (would've prefferred if John Cleese had been kept on, and had Ben Winshaw as his understudy), and the gadgets being cool new tech, but this film seems to have that. It also wasn't necessary for those latter things in an introductory film like Casino Royale, though I feel Quantum of Solace would've highly benefited, and Skyfall could've touched on it more like "cut off, we are going to have to be our own Q now" but Skyfall is still great. Spectre is underrated-don't care for the adoptive plot but the whole "base of Spectre" felt straight out of the actual book of You Only Live Twice, as opposed to that film which had...a volcano lair. Now if we can only get a proper director's cut of Quantum, it'd be really nice. 

I vote Tom Hiddleston as Bond and Clive Owen as the main villain with Idris Elba as a "bad agent" for the next "era" go-round.

Comment:
‚Äã@pigtailsboy  Everyone of Ian Fleming novels have been adapted already in some fashion. Even the short stories that did not get movies named after them had elements taken from them I.e. Bond In New York: Bond goes to warn a female agent that her boyfriend is an enemy spy (this is the last scene of Quantum of Solace). The Property of a Lady: Bond goes to an auction for Faberge jewelry to identify the owner who is involved in Espionage and potentially under bidding to drive up the price. (This plot and the name was used in Octopussy). Risico's plot was adapted completely in For Your Eyes Only. The Hildebrand Rarity had most of its elements adapted into Licence to Kill (Milton Krest and the stingray tail whip). I think the plot may have also been an influence on the Christopher Nolan film Tenet (the relationship between Andrei and Kat is similar to Krest and his wife). 

As it stands the only stories to actually not get adapted are The Spy Who Loved Me and the short stories Quantum of Solace, and a View to A Kill. The books has nothing in common with the movies beyond the title and their stories never really been adapted.

Comment:
¬†@danielt.4330¬† So as far as Bond films go, Casino Royal was fantastic and breathed new life into the character with a fresh actor. QoS had good action but the plot was so convoluted I can't even remember the bad guy's motivation. Craig's other Bond movies suffer from a similar problem. This one is different, however. It is going to make a mockery of Craig's Bond by playing him for a joke every chance they get. In addition, they're going to replace him with a diversity higher because of far left identitarian politics. I'd bet money this is going to go the way of Ghostbusters 2016, Captain Marvel, and the Star Wars sequels. It will see massive fan backlash as "toxic white male fans" watch yet another childhood hero reduced to a blabbering idiot drinking green alien tittie milk. This has been a trend in the film industry over the past 5 years. The whole plot of Picard is "Orange man bad" and old fans of star trek would vomit if they saw it. When your personal political views gets in the way of good storytelling, that's when it becomes a problem. George Lucas is NOT a conservative and Star Wars is an allagory for international conflicts in the real world, specifically desert storm. However, he didn't make Darth Vader some wimpy cry baby like his grandson Kylo Ren. He's supposed to be a sith apprentice who was trained by Luke Skywalker but Rey, who has had no training is able to defeat him.
This new 007 played by strong diverse female actor will suffer from the same problem Rey suffers from. She's going to be a Mary Sue. She's been an agent for 2 years and yet she could kick Bond's ass for breakfast. Everyone is going to like this character even when motivated not to, and she's probably not going to face any problems that can't be taken care of without breaking a sweat. 
I love James Bond, I love Star Wars, I love Ghostbusters, I love Star Trek, but the movies that have been coming out lately are not that. They take the characters that we all grew up with and tell you everything you believed in is wrong. They reduce these characters of "toxic masculinity" to the butt of a bad joke in order to prop up their new diverse female lead. These movies are made even worse by the actresses they choose to portray the character. Captain Marvel is played by a plank of wood. The Ghostbusters are played by female "comedians" who think that the key to a good joke is saying as loudly as possible. If cinema continues down this path, gone are the days of the classic male architype. No more Terminators, Bond's, Skywalkers, Kirks, etc. They're all figures of "toxic masculinity" and have no place in the new, far more progressive Hollywood.

Comment:
¬†@SkellaTore¬† She has not killed nearly enough people to talk to Bond in that condescending and arrogant tone.

On a related note, the Bond character has to be a man because the entire premise of every Bond film is that he is the man that all men dream of being and all women dream of sleeping with. He is suave, sophisticated, intelligent, charming, lives a life of danger and excitement, and easily seduces the most beautiful women in the world. This premise works, and it sells a lot of movie tickets.

A female 007 character is not nearly as appealing to audiences because it is natural for the bee to go from flower to flower, but not for the flower to go from bee to bee. In other words, a key that can open many locks is a great key - but a lock that is opened by many keys is a worthless piece of trash.

Is it a double standard? Yes, it definitely is. But it makes sense.

Comment:
Did Bond franchise improve over time?
That's something that's debatable as many are of the this & that opinion. 
Compared to these other franchises? No. It's not been as profitable. 
The franchise I believe has been struggling. 
Personally, I think it jumped the shark w/ Roger Moore's outlandish tomfoolery.  
Did James Bond Time To Die do well at the box office? The 'C' strongly affected it. 

Movies are evolving into a bleeding merge of streaming online. In fact, more are going straight to Hulu, Netflix, Prime & HBOMax. 
Theaters were dwindling before the C'. There weren't as many multi-complexes & now there's limited number of actual theaters. 
It's rare what happened to Encanto as it didn't fare well in theaters. Streaming it was an astounding success. 

This last movie signals a reboot. Another reboot shedding off old characters & start with fresh set of characters. I believe its w/ same blind mistakes made it not as popular. No, this isn't being 'woke' doing.  As for this Bond's death so be it, but why do this so pronounced? Did they do this w/ the other Bonds? No. Their chances were 'rebooted' between films w/o any notice or mention. Maybe there was a slight wink inside joke here & there. This death was an over the top reminiscent of Roger Moore's character. Interesting both Roger Moore & Sean Connery passed before this movie was made or interim. Wouldn't it have been a nice gesture to remember them? Nope do a 'reboot' ignoring them.

I grew up watching ALL the Bond movies. There's a lot of 'isms' elitism, racism, ageism & sexism. 
Remember the Bond movie he's surgically made to look Asian? (Whitewashing at its best).  Stems from producers, writers, directors coming from 'similar' backgrounds not aware of blindness or tone. It's not only this franchise, Star trek, Star Wars, Avengers and James Bond. Anyone remember Jar Jar Binks? (Irony George Lucas is married to a black woman & never saw the racist elements.)

Perspective helps in catching 'isms' as many are unbelievably blinded & don't/won't recognize. I being a female immediately watching the women on the screen can see an irritant that a younger woman is the love interest of Bond. People can date & marry of different ages. It's the issue it's common & accepted only younger women can date & marry the action lead. Kids in movies are either the brat or the kids wiser than their years. In this case, a 4year-old acts as if drugged? Doesn't squirm, get fussy or cry? How many kids easily go into the arms of a stranger? Not many. Who knows kids? Obviously not the director. Yeah, realism at its best. 

Blacks were far & in between in the early movies. Women? Bond girls beautiful, given sexist names, slept w/ Bond & weren't in movie for duration & if the love interest majority gone by next movie w/ exception Miss Moneypenny. 

As stated, it's not that great of a movie in my opinion. It got too long to keep interest on the story.
Stupid plot w/ weak hide & seek villain, actions scenes varied had weird plot holes. Exactly what was the villain's plan? 

Is it me, or did it sound a lot what many conspiracist's think about 'C' it was targeting certain people? 
Kill everyone or select people isn't that eugenics?? !
Is this what this plot was about? At one point the scientist mentions to 007 (a black woman) how he can select out her race including Africa? 
How come no one sees this negative racist/sexist plot shouldn't do? This is proof of the perspective blindness not realizing what the plot is.

Kill this group, that nation, race, culture, creed & whatever?  Makes no sense how the villain derives this thought process from the initial incident his family was killed by an evil Spectre hitman to all must die. No one realizes M had this brilliant eugenics idea? It doesn't dawn on M was acting in a similar manner as Hitler's eugenics agenda? It went over people's heads? Ok moving on...

A few words about diversity of this movie, had 3 blacks (1 killed), 1 Cuban/Spanish pretending to be American (We have a lot of Latinx/Cuban actresses) & 0 Asians. Really being inclusive, not really. Wondering about the Bond 'reboot' years from now. Curious if first movie be Casino Royale. (How many times will they reboot that one?)

Note Black Panter & Crazy Rich Asians surprised many critics assumed wouldn't garner a large audience ('white' people included) not having a white lead. Reason mentioned Black Panther is because it's supposed to be a hybrid of James Bond (traveling to different cities & adventures) & The Godfather (family dynamics added w/ an illegal son outsider). That's not 'my' words but the director. Oh, there's also a strong influence of women @ various ages & roles (mother, sister, friend/love interest & loyal protector).

I'm truly amazed at the number don't see the eugenics plot? Unbelievable.

Comment: I was looking forward to enjoying a long awaited enjoyable night out seeing a movie in a cinema. What I got in this latest Bond franchise was boring, prolonged, filled with huge pedestrian script fillers between the action scenes and an ending that must have Ian Fleming fuming! Perhaps because Craig was listed in the credits as being the lead actor and involved in production and knowing it was his final hurrah in the role, he decided to kill off two enduring villains and then the ultimate lunacy, himself, thus rendering any future actor with the task of true resurrection! This film is pure garbage and why they bothered boring the Royal Family with a special gala viewing is astonishing. When Bond opted to leave the new high tech Aston Martin parked in the woods and attempt an escape in some SUV, after having blitzed everybody earlier in the original version, was equally idiotic. Rotten Tomatoes can line this junk up for an award. It even took about 20 minutes into the film before the action began. The people who were entrusted with this franchise simply ran out of enthusiasm. Hopefully, it moves into much better hands. I have watched 007 since the ‚Äò60‚Äôs; this film is only licensed to be put into the rubbish. üëéüèΩü§¨
